ce:section.ce:para:
To elucidate the role of sodium sulfide in enhancing hydrogen production, it primarily relies on the dissociation of sulfide ions (S2−
                     ) in water, while sodium sulfite relies on the dissociation of sulfite ions (SO3
                     2−
                     ). These dissociated ions act as electron donors that effectively capture holes, leading to an irreversible reaction. This process promotes efficient charge separation, facilitating hydrogen generation through water splitting [40,43]. This study further investigates the photocatalytic hydrogen production efficiency of N-doped CDs/In-doped ZnS heterostructures using various ratios of sodium sulfide and sodium sulfite as sacrificial agents, as illustrated in Fig. 8c. The findings show that a 3:1 sodium sulfite to sodium sulfide ratio exhibits the highest hydrogen production efficiency during photocatalytic water splitting. Additionally, using sodium sulfite or sodium sulfide alone produces lower efficiency than their combined use. Previous studies have indicated that mixing these two sacrificial agents effectively enhances photocatalytic efficiency [46,47]. The mechanism is hypothesized to involve sulfide ions capturing holes from the valence band, forming polysulfide ions. Sulfite ions inhibit these polysulfide ions from reacting with protons, forming thiosulfate ions (S2O3
                     2−
                     ) and sulfide ions (S2−
                     ) [40]. Thiosulfate's colorless nature ensures it does not interfere with the photocatalyst's light absorption, allowing more efficient light utilization. This characteristic helps explain why combining sacrificial agents, including thiosulfate, leads to higher hydrogen production efficiency than using sodium sulfide or sodium sulfite individually [43,48].
